This award enabled the PI, David Ayala, to conduct research in homotopy theory related to manifold geometry, deformation theory, and categorification.  This is an abstract approach to structural questions in quantum physics.  Specifically, the PI collaborated with John Francis, Nick Rozenblyum, Aaron Mazel-Gee, and Adam Howard on the development of factorization homology, which is a pairing between manifolds (geometry) and higher-categories (algebra).  Such manifolds abstrat world-sheets; such higher categories are generated through deformation theory; factorization homology codifies and abstracts global observables of a topologically-invariant quantum field theory.  The technical groundwork for these developments is that of stratifications: stratified spaces and stratified categories.  All of these developments are publically available as a series of nine articles.  


This award enabled the completion of four PhD theses in the subject of algebraic topology:

Configuration spaces and exit-path categories by Anna Cepek; 
A contact manifold is the quotient of a metric tree by a profinite group by Daniel Perry; 
Additivity for factorization algebras by Eric Berry; 
A classification of immersions from surfaces by Adam Howard.


This award enabled the disemination of these research findings by way of a book, a book chapter, several peer-reviewed journal articles, organization of four international conferences and workshops, four international lecture series, and many conference and seminar presentations.  This award also enabled the writing of a draft of an undergraduate topology textbook focused on salient and novel examples that are representative of current practice and applicaiton of the subject.  




